1. Calculate the energy levels for \( n=3 \) and \( n=2 \):
   \[
   E_3 = -\frac{13.6 \, \text{eV} \times 26^2}{3^2} = -\frac{13.6 \times 676}{9} \approx -1022.22 \, \text{eV}
   \]
   \[
   E_2 = -\frac{13.6 \, \text{eV} \times 26^2}{2^2} = -\frac{13.6 \times 676}{4} \approx -2300.4 \, \text{eV}
   \]

2. Calculate the energy difference \( \Delta E \):
   \[
   \Delta E = E_2 - E_3 = -2300.4 \, \text{eV} - (-1022.22 \, \text{eV}) = -1278.18 \, \text{eV}
   \]
   The magnitude of the energy difference is \( 1278.18 \, \text{eV} \).

3. Convert the energy difference to Joules:
   \[
   1278.18 \, \text{eV} \times 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J/eV} \approx 2.047 \times 10^{-16} \, \text{J}
   \]

4. Calculate the wavelength using the energy of the photon:
   \[
   \lambda = \frac{hc}{E}
   \]
   where \( h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J s} \) and \( c = 2.998 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \):
   \[
   hc = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \times 2.998 \times 10^8 \approx 1.986 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{J m}
   \]
   \[
   \lambda = \frac{1.986 \times 10^{-25}}{2.047 \times 10^{-16}} \approx 9.69 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} = 0.969 \, \text{Angstroms}
   \]

5. Round to two significant figures:
   \[
   \lambda \approx 0.97 \, \text{Angstroms}
   \]
